@article{shadleCapitalismFutureAmerican2022,
  title = {Capitalism and the {{Future}} of {{American Classical Music Scholarship}}},
  author = {Shadle, Douglas W.},
  year = 2022,
  month = dec,
  journal = {American Music},
  volume = {40},
  number = {4},
  pages = {567--570},
  publisher = {Duke University Press},
  issn = {0734-4392},
  doi = {10.5406/19452349.40.4.24},
  urldate = {2025-02-08},
  abstract = {Perhaps no historical composer has sparked more public interest in recent memory than Florence Price (1888--1953). Since 2018, when Alex Ross of the New Yorker and musicologist Micaela Baranello reported on the world premiere recording of Price's two violin concertos in expansive contextual essays, global performances of her music have skyrocketed, even despite the COVID-19 pandemic. As one scholar among many endeavoring to build on biographical work by pioneers like Barbara Garvey Jackson, Mildred Denby Green, and Rae Linda Brown, I've come face to face with impediments to scholarship on American classical music embedded in the webs of contemporary global capitalism manifested in the classical music industry. This essay offers reflections on a few of these challenges.Documents in the Rae Linda Brown papers held at Emory University indicate that Price scholars and performers ran into significant difficulty discerning who managed the rights to Price's catalog after her daughter's death in 1975. By the mid-1990s, however, one of Price's grandchildren had teamed with Brown to negotiate with publishers on the Price estate's behalf, thus solving a major quandary. During the two decades prior to Brown's tragic death in 2017, Barbara Garvey Jackson's boutique publishing house, ClarNan Editions, released nearly thirty editions of Price's smaller works, while Brown herself edited Price's Sonata in E Minor and two of her symphonies for G. Schirmer and A-R Editions, respectively. Even so, a substantial percentage of Price's catalog remained unpublished, available only in manuscript at the Special Collections division at the University of Arkansas Mullins Library.Not long after Ross's and Baranello's reporting in 2018, G. Schirmer acquired the global rights to Price's catalog after reaching an agreement with her grandchildren. The prospect of international marketing and rapid publication of Price's orchestral works felt generative at the time, but technical problems rapidly emerged. What would happen to the portion of the catalog published during Brown's time as an agent, such as the critical edition of the first and third symphonies she prepared with Wayne Shirley? Or the edited but unpublished scores used for the world premiere recordings of Price's violin concertos, fourth symphony, and chamber music? In some but not all cases, Schirmer created new editions, settling certain questions about ownership but raising new ones about the broader marketplace of orchestral music.Although Schirmer had published Price's Song to the Dark Virgin (1941) during her lifetime, president Robert Thompson explained after the acquisition, ``It's my hope that Florence Price's contribution to the canon of American music will finally be recognized and properly assessed. She has been neglected for too long.'' Of course, that neglect stemmed partly from his firm's own disinterest in four decades of growing Price scholarship. With such a splashy entrance into the marketplace and the promise of enabling orchestras to program more diverse composers, Schirmer had a vested interest in making as much of Price's music available as quickly as possible. Yet, perhaps counterintuitively, an emphasis on speed and profitability has inhibited performance and scholarship on certain fronts.According to my understanding of current U.S. copyright law, Price's unpublished manuscripts will enter the public domain in January 2024. At the time of the acquisition, Schirmer therefore had five years to extract as much profit as possible from the Price catalog before others could freely pursue their own projects. Indeed, the cost of renting Price's orchestral works is prohibitively expensive for smaller organizations, thus limiting its accessibility despite the promise of global availability. In October 2021, a staff member at a moderately sized orchestra in the South publicly disclosed that the rental fee for Price's piano concerto cost the ensemble \$2,200, or over \$100 per minute of this relatively brief work. A standard rental agreement obliges the orchestra to return the scores and parts without keeping a copy with bowings and other interpretive markings in the orchestra's library for future use. Schirmer also charges a per-measure fee for music examples published in books or journals, as is their right. Yet the fee dissuades analytical scholarship in the near term since it will no longer be necessary for writers who can create their own examples from the unpublished manuscripts after 2023.Complicating matters, Price's unpublished manuscripts contain typical errors, such as wrong notes, missing accidentals, and other small items that can be fixed with careful attention to detail. Schirmer's editions have replicated many of these errors while introducing others during the engraving process, leaving conductors, orchestra librarians, players, and scholars to fend for themselves if they lack access to the manuscripts. In my experience working on this repertoire, I've learned that a growing coterie of conductors and librarians privately circulates errata developed from the available primary sources. This detailed---and ostensibly necessary!---work is essentially unpaid labor that benefits Schirmer by enhancing performances that might otherwise fall flat with the provided materials. (The Schirmer editors pressured to create workable editions as quickly and as cheaply as possible certainly also deserve sympathy.)Meanwhile, public desire for information about Price and her milieu has grown in tandem with performance opportunities. Responding to this demand, ensembles and media organizations have needed to supply their patrons with educational materials that are routinely available for many other composers: program notes, preconcert talks, podcasts, blog entries, radio broadcasts, and so on. But how much research about Price is widely available for creators of this material who find background on other composers with relative ease? ``The necessary evidence to write a detailed biography of Florence Price,'' Brown observed in her own Price biography, ``is surprisingly scant.''1 The mismatch between the desire for and availability of high-quality educational information exposes how frequently these organizations rely on, or in some cases exploit, scholarly labor while generating multidisciplinary experiences for their patrons.None of what I have written above is unique to Price; a critical edition of George Gershwin's music, all of which will enter the public domain by 2034, shares similar technical, financial, and legal challenges. But Price's situation offers a glimpse into the broader machinery of the classical music marketplace today. After the murder of George Floyd in May 2020, for example, many American classical music organizations publicly committed to diversify their programming, which has further enabled the profit-seeking behaviors of monopolistic stakeholders like Schirmer. Even music in the public domain like that of Joseph Bologne, Chevalier de Saint-Georges, comes with a hefty rental fee. And unpublished music by Black composers who lived well into the twentieth century, such as Julia Perry and William Dawson, is still difficult to obtain.The same could also be said of countless American composers active in the early twentieth century whose music remains absent from concert stages today. While studying Price and her world, I've encountered composers whose names were completely unfamiliar to me as a longtime scholar of earlier orchestral music: Radie Britain (1899--1994), Eric DeLamarter (1880--1953), Thorvald Otterstr\"om (1868--1942), Florence Grandland Galajikian (1900--1970), and Robert L. Sanders (1906--1974), to name but a few active in Chicago. Of course, my ignorance in no way suggests that other scholars have never written on these individuals---the Greenwood Bio-Bibliography series has a terrific volume on Radie Britain, for example. But it's clear to me that some of the same legal and financial impediments to Price performance and scholarship have long affected these composers, too, to say nothing of more familiar names like Leo Sowerby (1895--1968) and Robert Russell Bennett (1894--1981).Radie Britain offers a case in point worth examining in more detail. Her music manuscripts are available in research libraries, yet her unpublished music won't enter the public domain for another forty years. The bio-bibliography lists a now-defunct family-owned publishing house as the copyright holder. What can be done on her behalf without the well-supported estates of composers like Gershwin and Aaron Copland, whose earnings dwarfed those of Britain and Price in an industry that was openly discriminatory toward women and composers of color? Even with adequate financial support, the musicological academy has effectively ceased rewarding the production of critical editions, leaving such advocacy of ``unknown'' composers open only to risktakers. But, as scholars have long argued, generating a broader, more diverse historical portrait of classical music in this country---one that moves beyond outdated narratives of White- and male-dominated modernism---requires direct engagement with musical, biographical, and contextual information that is already difficult to find, much less synthesize.2What can be done to improve a situation that stands outside any one person's control? Scholarly collaboration seems key since complex historiography benefits from multiple perspectives.3 In my experience at least, staff at performing organizations are also becoming more aware of their incapacity to generate engaging humanities content without direct scholarly input. These organizations should engage scholars---and pay them. Finally, my colleague Joy Calico and I have discussed the potential for new tools like music encoding to offer more sustainable alternatives to conventional publication that could be mutually beneficial for scholars and composer estates while enhancing global accessibility with remote technologies. Rae Linda Brown's decades-long pursuit of creative solutions to vexing problems laid the groundwork for the Florence Price explosion of the last several years. May her inventive spirit continue to refresh a scholarly enterprise grappling with increasingly unsustainable demands on time, labor, and financial resources.},
  langid = {english},
  keywords = {ungelesen}
}

